article.headline: New York earns its first victory
article.linkText: Johnson's 23 helps Liberty beat old coach Adubato
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- After winning all those games with Richie
Adubato, the New York Liberty found it strange trying to beat him.

"It was very weird," guard Vickie Johnson said.

The Liberty got the best of their old coach Wednesday night,
pulling away for a 77-68 victory over the Washington Mystics in a
game that was tight throughout until New York made a late run.

Adubato coached New York for 5½ seasons, leading the team to
three conference titles and a 100-79 record, before he was fired
last July. He was hired by the Mystics in April and said before the
game he still knows his old team better than his new one.

"He knows our stuff. We know his stuff," Johnson said. "We
knew it was going to be a matter of executing at the end."

Johnson had 23 points, 10 rebounds and six assists to help New
York (1-2) avoid its first 0-3 start since 1999. She made 9 of 12
field goals, including all four of her 3-point attempts.

"If I was coaching Vickie Johnson again, I'd be very happy with
her performance," Adubato said. "She's a veteran player. She has
a lot of heart, and she knew her team needed this win today."

Becky Hammon added 13 points and five assists for the Liberty,
who shot 55 percent from the field and 57 percent from 3-point
range. After getting beaten badly on the boards in their first two
games -- 84-55 combined -- New York outrebounded Washington 28-20.
Ann Wauters grabbed seven rebounds to go with her 11 points.

Chasity Melvin scored 16 points on 7-for-9 shooting to lead the
Mystics, but she fouled out with 4:24 to play. Temeka Johnson added
13 points and 11 assists. Washington (1-3) has lost three straight,
all at home.

"You're supposed to win at home," Adubato said. "But it's
very, very early, and we understand that we're going to be keep on
improving and getting better, and we'll be able to turn this thing
around. But, obviously, it's urgent."

The Mystics were again missing guard Alana Beard, who has yet to
play this season because of a sprained right ankle. Delisha
Milton-Jones was sidelined with a strained right knee.

Neither team led by more than six until Vickie Johnson's
three-point play with 4:24 remaining put the Liberty ahead 67-60.
Wauters later added a pair of inside baskets to cap a 16-6 run and
make the score 73-62.

The Mystics made a pair of 3-pointers in the final minute to cut
the deficit to five, but Hammon made two free throws with 19
seconds left for the final margin.
